                        title: 'PERCUSSION PISTOLS',
                        desc: 'Percussion firing system didn’t lead to significant changes in general design of pistols. For a long time European gun-makers were making both flintlock and percussion pistols at the same time using very often same pistol parts for both systems. Development of design, decoration style and manufacturing technology of percussion pistols were based on technical solutions proven in the manufacturing of flintlock pistols.<br>Pistols began to be used more and more for sport. Target pistols were manufactured in matching pairs with a set of accessories. Soon, new designs of small caliber (5-10 mm) pistols appeared. They were intended for indoor use, and that is why those guns were called parlor pistols – (zimmerpistole). These small dimensions pistols that could be carried in a pocket were very popular at the time. Most of them had box shaped lock with separate breech block and barrels.',
